					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-11270454#post-4225294</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-11270454/scp-4589#post-4225294</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sun, 21 Apr 2019 07:01:42 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>The Great Hippo</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>3938622</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <blockquote> <p>Notably, SCP-4589 cultures do not divide as normal cultures would, instead, they continue to grow steadily and develop pseudopods, limbs, and rudimentary sensory organs.</p> </blockquote> <p>The comma between &quot;would&quot; and &quot;instead&quot; ought to be a semicolon (otherwise, this is a comma splice).</p> <p>This didn't work for me. The core idea is neat, but the premise alone isn't strong enough to carry the execution. Unlike, say, your <a href="http://www.scpwiki.com/scp-3794">salsa hammer skip</a>, there's more I need to see here to make it &quot;work&quot;. It's not enough that you tell me about this fleshy mass of tissue; you need to <em>show</em> me. Either directly (via logs) or indirectly (where we somehow explore its consequences or the people involved in it).</p> <p>It reminds me of the second half of <a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xenogears">Xenogears</a>. It's an old JRPG where they ran over budget mid-way through production &#8212; so the last quarter of the game consists of characters telling you about the content rather than you playing through it (I'm not even making this up; they literally sit down, look at the screen, and tell you what happened in the dungeons you never got to visit).</p> <p>This can work when the content is a short, fun punchline or a compelling idea that stands on its own, but when it's like the image you're trying to evoke here, we need to experience it in a way that goes beyond a brief summary.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
